[The musk ox or muskox (_Ovibos moschatus_), a member of the Bovidae
family, is a mammal of the Arctic region noted for its strong odor
and thick coat. The strong odor is given off by the males primarily
and is used for attracting females during mating season. Generally
this animal lives in the Arctic regions of North America but there
are populations of the animal in Norway, Sweden, and areas of Siberia.

The musk ox has developed several adaptations to such an extremely
cold climate. The most useful adaptation has been its coat (Gray
1990). The coat is made of 2 layers. The outermost is a thick shaggy
coat, possibly the longest of all the animals (Scholastic 2008). They
also have a hairy under layer called the qiviut. The qiviut has
financial value due to its cashmere texture and ability to trap in
heat (Lent 1988). Musk oxen shed their under wool in spring and by
the end of summer have a new qiviut layer (Lent 1988). As well as
practical winter wear, the thick fur of musk oxen is useful in the
summer. The long hair provides defense against the mosquitoes, making
it so the only flesh vulnerable is on the nose (Scholastic 2008). The
hooves are also well suited for the climate that the musk ox
inhabits, the sharp rims are ideal for cutting into snow and the
broadness of the heels serves as sufficient traction when climbing
snowy ridges (Tener 1965). Musk oxen are adapted to the weather down
to their tail. The tail is thought to be short to help maintain
warmth in the winter because shorter appendages take fewer calories
to keep warm (Tener 1965). The tail is short also because it is not
needed to swat away mosquitoes (Tener 1965). Musk oxen also have
sharp chins that they can use to break through ice and snow in the
winter to find suitable vegetation (Gray 1986).

Musk oxen are generally large and relatively fearsome animals,
weighing between 400 and 800 pounds [180-360 kg] and standing about 5
feet [1.5 m] at the shoulder. While that is smaller than many beef
breeds of cattle, the hair makes them seem much larger. During
breeding season the bulls are quite aggressive, even charging birds
that may be too close to their personal space.

They are a social creature, often found in herds of 10-20 of both
males and females, except during breeding season when there may be
small groups of bachelor or unsuccessful bulls as the stronger bull
will run all others from the herd.

Mineral deficiencies are well documented in other bovidae animals, so
it seems quite reasonable that these creatures may be similar. The
specialized hair is likely going to require a different balance than
other bovidae.

Hopefully a good nutrition lab can analyze the forage and feed and
supplements and start getting them on the right track. Likewise, with
a research herd in captivity for this many years, hopefully they have
established 'normals' of the biological parameters to help determine
how these animals are recovering.

Photos of musk ox may be found at
<http://www.cowart.info/blog/2009/06/thinking-about-musk-ox.html> and
<http://www.bio.davidson.edu/people/vecase/Behavior/Spring2008/Merrill/habitat%20and%20distribution.html>.

Portions of this comment have been extracted from
<http://www.bio.davidson.edu/people/vecase/Behavior/Spring2008/Merrill/habitat%20and%20distribution.html>
- Mod.TG]

